{{Short description|Hawaiian school bullying incidents}} {{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox event | title = Kill Haole Day | image = | image_size = | image_upright = | image_alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | english_name = | time = | duration = | date = The second to last day of school (May or June) | venue = | location = [[Hawaii]], U.S. | coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|region:XXXX_type:event|display=inline,title}} --> | also_known_as = | type = | theme = | cause = | first_reporter = | budget = | patron = <!-- or |patrons= --> | organisers = <!-- or |organizers= --> | filmed_by = | participants = | outcome = | casualties1 = | casualties2 = | casualties3 = | reported deaths = | reported injuries = | reported missing = | reported property damage = | burial = | inquiries = | inquest = | coroner = | arrests = | suspects = | accused = | convicted = | charges = | trial = | verdict = | convictions = | sentence = | publication_bans = | litigation = | awards = | url = | blank_label = <!-- or |blank_data= --> | blank1_label = <!-- or |blank1_data= --> | blank2_label = <!-- or |blank2_data= --> | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | notes = }} '''Kill Haole Day''' is the term for bullying incidents that occurred in some public [[Hawaii]] schools, when non-white students would harass and attack white students.<ref>{{cite news | newspaper=The Los Angeles Times | title=Hawaii's Ethnic Mix Reflected by Tension in Schools | page=3 | date=July 15, 1979 | last=Freed | first=Kenneth | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/99973600/kill-haole-day-lat/}}</ref> (''[[Haole]]'' is a Hawaiian term for individuals who are not Native Hawaiian.) Kill Haole Day was discussed by the [[Hawaii State Legislature]] when debating hate crimes legislation in 1999, despite the lack of documented incidents.<ref name=rohrer>{{cite book | last=Rohrer | first=J. | title=Haoles in Hawaii | publisher=University of Hawaii Press | series=Race and Ethnicity in Hawai'i | year=2010 | isbn=978-0-8248-6042-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gYwBEAAAQBAJ&pg=PA79 | access-date=April 18, 2022 | pages=79â€“80}}</ref>
In his 2009 book, lawyer and former Hawai{{okina}}i governor [[Ben Cayetano]] wrote that "Kill Haole Day" began as a news story headline about an incident between haole and local (not just Hawaiian) students. After that, "whenever there was a fight or an incident between haole and non-haole students, the news media", and newspaper editorial boards, "repeatedly reprised 'Kill Haole Day' in their news stories".<ref>Cayetano, Ben. ''Ben: A Memoir, From Street Kid to Governor'' (Watermark, 2009), p. 531</ref>
In 1999, School Superintendent Paul LeMahieu said he was aware of "Kill Haole Day" but not of any significant incidents. Also, in 1999, it was an issue during debate on [[hate crimes]] legislation.<ref name="starbulletin">{{cite web|url=http://starbulletin.com/1999/03/24/news/story7.html|title='Kill haole day' linked to hate-crime bill | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040112071545/http://starbulletin.com/1999/03/24/news/story7.html | archive-date=January 12, 2004}}</ref>{{r|rohrer}}
On December 31, 2008, the [[United States Department of Education|U.S. Department of Education]] released a report on Kealakehe Intermediate School in [[Kailua-Kona, Hawaii|Kailua-Kona]] that concluded there was "substantial evidence that students experienced racially and sexually derogatory name-calling on nearly a daily basis on school buses, at school bus stops, in school hallways and other areas of the school".<ref>{{cite web|author=United States Department of Education - Office for Civil Rights|title=OCR Reference No 10051060|url=http://stopsexualassaultinschools.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/OCR-FOIA-cases-Hawaii.pdf}}</ref>
The report also concluded that school officials responded inadequately or not at all when students complained of racial harassment. Students who did complain were retaliated against by their antagonists.<ref>{{cite news|website=Southern Poverty Law Center | last=Keller | first=Larry|title=Hawaii Suffering From Racial Prejudice|url=http://www.splcenter.org/get-informed/intelligence-report/browse-all-issues/2009/fall/prejudice-in-paradise| url-status=dead | archive-date=August 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829125639/https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/intelligence-report/2009/hawaii-suffering-racial-prejudice}}</ref>
